All I need is a portable hole full of beer and a major land battle.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uhuzurdadi.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Huzurdadi</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(4/8/02 7:11:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovegeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27012.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Why beat around the bush?</span><hr size=1> So what's the current ratio between cleric healing (powered by CH) and druid healing?<br>
<br>
The best druid heal (Nature's Touch) has a ratio of something like 2.5.<br>
<br>
CH has a ratio of something like 10 (assuming that it heals 4k HP, it can heal more at high level, but let's use this as a base line).<br>
<br>
So by the mana ratio metric clerics heal x4 as well as druids.<br>
<br>
Imagine if you will if Direct Damage scaled in the same way between wizards and druids. Or heck between any two classes. Let's compare wizards and clerics! <br>
<br>
The best (non bane) wizard spell does 1.2k damage with a mana ratio of 4. The best cleric spell does 925 damage with a ratio of ~3. <br>
<br>
If Cleric DDs were held to the same standard that they want other class's healing to be held to they would have a nuke of 300 points of damage with a mana ratio of 1. LOL! People would die of laughter if Verant had proposed such insanity. Yet people accept it for clerics for some mysterious reason (perhaps because clerics have always threatened to withhold rezes? I don't know).<br>
<br>
Heck, let's compare the ratio between druids and wizards for nuking. People currently think that the ratio is 'fair.' Moonfire does ~1100 points of damage for 450 mana. That's a ratio of 2.4. Wizards do about 1.2k with Ice Spear of Solist for 300 mana. That's a ratio of 4. Thus the ratio between wizards and druids is 1.666. <br>
<br>
Thus, it would follow that giving druids a CH that costs 700 mana or so would be in line with other specialist vs. generalists.<br>
